What the Pollsters Got Wrong: An Analysis of the 2016 Election Predictions

Courtney Sweeney

11-14-2025

What the Pollsters Got Wrong: An Analysis of the 2016 Election Predictions

A step-by-step guide to data wrangling using two datasets

The 2016 presidential election sent shock waves throughout the country. This wasnt just because of the result, but because polls made it seem as though Clinton would win in a landslide. For Democrats, understanding what went wrong during this campaign is incredibly important to both understanding their opposition and engineering campaigns that can win.

For pollsters, this data is also important so they can increase the accuracy of their polls in the future.

The Datasets

The two datasets used in this tutorial are from the dslabs package. They are polls_us_election_2016 and results_us_election_2016.

The polls_us_election_2016 set includes information about 4208 polls that were conducted at various times leading up to the election. Every row includes a state, pollster, pollster grade, start and end dates, sample size, and poll numbers for every candidate.

The results_us_election_2016 set includes the election results for every state. Every row includes a state, the elector votes, and the percentage of votes for each candidate.

An Introduction to Data Wrangling

1. Set-Up

The first steps of data wrangling include loading packages and data sets. In R, packages that can be used for datawrangling include tidyverse, dplyr, mdsr, and mosaic.

To load data sets, store data from packages in variables (ex: polls <- polls_us_election_2016). If a data set is being imported, click import and copy and paste the code that is displayed in this pop-up window.

2. Cleaning the Data

To get data into a usable form, the data must first be cleaned. This requires multiple steps that depend on the type of data that is present.

Select()

The select() function creates either a new database or replaces the old database (depending on assignment) with only the columns chosen by the user.

Here, the select() function uses - to denote that those columns are not selected. This was used because there were more columns being kept than being excluded.

Sometimes, datasets have extra information that is not needed by the user for their analysis. This is when select() is useful in data cleaning.

hilary_trump <- select(polls, -population, -samplesize, 
                       -rawpoll_mcmullin, -adjpoll_mcmullin, 
                       -rawpoll_johnson, -adjpoll_johnson)

Na.omit()

The na.omit() function omits rows that have values with NA as the value. NA is Rs empty value, such as none or null in other languages.

Missing data can be very problematic when doing data analysis. One of the ways that missing data can be dealt with is listwise deletion. Listwise deletion is when entire rows are deleted with any missing data. Here, I used pairwise deletion. I selected only the columns that I needed first and then removed all of the entries where the pollster had a missing grade, as that was the only column with missing data left.

Dealing with missing data is typically one of the first steps when cleaning data.

#cleans the hilary_trump data
hilary_trump <- na.omit(hilary_trump)

Filter()

Filtering data is used to select specific rows with specific values.

Here, the data is filtered based on the state variable. != means that the rows are selected when the state is NOT U.S..

The results that were contained in the other dataset are for every state and doesnt include the U.S. as a whole, which is why the U.S. rows are being eliminated.

#filters for non-US rows
hilary_trump <- filter(hilary_trump, state!="U.S.")

Arrange()

The arrange() function is used to sort or rank data based on a specific variable. It can also be used with multiple variables.

Here, the data in hilary_trump is being sorted first by grade (in descending order) then enddate (also in descending order).

This is so that polls can be in order based on their pollster grade then by date to do tests about the best pollsters.

hilary_trump <- arrange(hilary_trump, desc(grade), 
                        desc(enddate))

Distinct()

The distinct() function chooses rows based on a variable specified in the function. It only allows for one instance of every value for that variable.

Here, it is used to get the results from the highest rated pollsters that were the most recent for each state.

#This finds distinct entries for every state
unique_ht = hilary_trump %>%
  distinct(state, .keep_all=TRUE) %>% 
  arrange(state)

Left_join()

Joins are used to connect two datasets or dataframes.

Left_join() is used to connect tables when all of the values from the first table must be kept, and the values from the second match the first.

Here, every value from unique_ht and hilary_trump must be preserved. This is because there are more rows in these and multiple instances of every state.

The results dataset contains just one row for each state, so those results need to be applied to every column.

Joins also must be done on a variable. The variable chosen here is state, as that is what the two data sets have in common.

#joined by state
joined1 <- left_join(unique_ht, results, by="state") 
joined2 <- left_join(hilary_trump, results, by="state")

In the final data set, the information from results is added onto the end of the row for each state. Each row begins with the information from the original dataset (startdate, pollster, etc) then finishes with the electoral votes and actual percentages.

There are multiple other join types that can be used: right_join(), full_join(), and anti_join().

Mutate()

The mutate() function creates new variables.

This is important when information needs to be created for each row from existing information. This can vary depending on the dataset.

joined1 = joined1 %>%
  #declares the poll winner, adds a variable that contains that information
  mutate(poll_winner = if_else(adjpoll_clinton>adjpoll_trump, 
                               "Clinton", "Trump")) %>% 
  
  #does the same as above, but with the actual winner 
  mutate(winner = if_else(clinton>trump, "Clinton", "Trump")) %>% 
  
  #determines if the winner was correct
  mutate(correct = if_else(poll_winner==winner, TRUE, FALSE))  

joined2 = joined2 %>%
  mutate(poll_winner = if_else(adjpoll_clinton>adjpoll_trump, 
                               "Clinton", "Trump")) %>%
  mutate(winner = if_else(clinton>trump, "Clinton", "Trump")) %>%
  mutate(correct = if_else(poll_winner==winner, TRUE, FALSE)) %>%
  
  #This next section determines the "direction" of the poll and the winner. 
  #If the winner is correct, then the value is "true". 
  #If the value is "CT", then Clinton was predicted and Trump won. If 
  #it was "TC", Trump was predicted and Hilary won. 
  
  mutate(dir_winner = case_when(poll_winner==winner~"TRUE",
                              poll_winner=="Clinton"&winner=="Trump"~"CT", 
                              poll_winner=="Trump"&winner=="Clinton"~"TC")) %>%
  
  #This adds a variable with the error found for Clinton's 
  #polling and actual results. 
  #The absolute value is used to standardize it.
  
  mutate(clinton_error = abs(adjpoll_clinton-clinton)) %>%
  #This does the same for Trump
  mutate(trump_error = abs(adjpoll_trump-trump))

3. Organizing the Data

The next section contains various functions from above in order to continue to organize the data.

Now that the data is organized and cleaned into a few different datasets, it can be manipulated to get more specific information.

#This tallies the variable "dir_winner" from joined2 to see

tally(~joined2$dir_winner)

joined2 <- na.omit(joined2) #cleans data

Group_by() & Summarize()

The group_by() function is typically used with a summarizing function.

Here, it is used with summarize(). The summarize() function is used with other functions like mean(). Mean() gets the average of a variable.

In this function, group_by() groups by state, then the average error for each candidate for each state is found.

wrong_swings_error = wrong_swings %>%
  group_by(state) %>%
  summarize(avg_error_trump = mean(trump_error), 
            avg_error_clinton = mean(clinton_error))

head(wrong_swings_error, 3)
## # A tibble: 3  3
##   state    avg_error_trump avg_error_clinton
##   <chr>              <dbl>             <dbl>
## 1 Florida             4.27              1.34
## 2 Iowa               10.6               2.51
## 3 Michigan            7.40              3.39

This showcases which states had the highest average errors.

Pivot()

The pivot() function changes the format of the dataframe.

A long dataset has values that do repeat in the first column.

A wide dataset does not repeat values in the first column.

Depending on the situation, both can be useful. Here, the pivots are to create graphs. Graphs often use levels of variables or factors to display information.

To pivot_longer, like it is done here, follow this format:

long_df <- pivot_longer(df, cols=2:4, names_to=Name, values_to=Amount)

  • cols = columns to be transformed into one column
  • names_to = the title of the column being created
  • values_to = the new column created with the values originally in every column
#pivoting wrong_swings_error to a long format from wide
wrong_swings_error_long <- pivot_longer(wrong_swings_error, 
                                        cols=2:3, names_to="Candidate", 
                                        values_to="error") 

#pivoting wrong_swings to a long format from wide
wrong_swings_long <- pivot_longer(wrong_swings, cols=18:19, 
                                  names_to="candidate", values_to="error")

#selecting certain columns
wrong_swings_long <- select(wrong_swings_long, state, startdate, 
                            enddate, pollster, grade, candidate, error)

actual_results <- data.frame(

  y = c(47.3, 46.5, 47.9),
  State=c("Michigan", "Wisconsin", "Pennsylvania")
)

5. Visualization

Scatterplot of Swing States

This graph is a visualization of polling results from three key swing states: Michigan, Pennsylvania, Wisconsin, and North Carolina. Combined, they provide 46 electoral votes. While these states alone wouldnt have been enough to push Clinton to a victory, they were states that consistently polled for Clinton to win.

On the graph, there is a line with a slope of 1. Above this line signifies a Clinton win prediction, while below signifies a Trump win prediction. The majority of the points on this graph are above the line, signifying Clinton predictions.

The actual results are signified in the same color as the polling results but with a black outline. All three fall under the line, as all three states ended up voting for Trump.

ggplot(swings, aes(x=adjpoll_trump, y=adjpoll_clinton)) +geom_point(aes(color=State)) + geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, linetype="dashed") + geom_point(data=actual_results, aes(x=x, y=y, fill=State), shape = 21, size=3, stroke=1.2, color="black") + theme_minimal() + labs (x="Trump (%)", y="Clinton (%)", title="Trump vs Clinton Polling Predictions", subtitle="A visualization of how few pollsters got the 2016 results correct", caption="Data from dslabs package")

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/36541086/adding-an-extra-point-in-a-ggplot2-graph https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/geom_point.html

From this graph, we can gather that pollsters were overwhelmingly wrong about Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin in particular.

If there was more information about the polling conducted to yield such inaccurate results, it would be very useful to see what factors may have contributed to this so that pollsters dont make similar errors.

While it would be impossible for every poll to yield the correct results, there should be improvement so that there isnt such a large error as shown here.

Histogram of Polling Error

This graph shows the frequency of different errors between the polls that took place in Pennsylvania that predicted the election wrong. Since Trump won Pennsylvania, all of the results are from polls that incorrectly predicted Clinton would win.

While polls that correctly predicted Trump winning would also have an error, this focuses on only polls that completely got it wrong.

For Clinton, the error is how many points she was overestimated by. For Trump, the error is how many points he was underestimated by.

ggplot(penn, aes(x=error)) + geom_histogram(fill="red", color="black", bins=15) + facet_wrap(~candidate, labeller=as_labeller(c("clinton_error"="Clinton (Amount Above Actual Result)", "trump_error"="Trump (Amount Below Actual Result)"))) + labs(y="Frequency", x="Error Between Polling and Results", title="Pennsylvania Error Margins, 2016 Presidential Election")+theme_minimal()

What this graph shows is that the error surrounding Trump was normally distributed, with the center at around 6 or 7. This means that Trump was underestimated by typically around 6 or 7 points. This is a substantial difference between polling and actual results.
